Block ping to the Gateway IP from both the clients. 
Block ping from client1 to client2 .
Save the rules on the firewall VM.
Flush the rules in the FORWARD chain of the Firewall VM.
Now install apache web server on client1. Start the service. Add your index.html file.
Block access to this website from Firewall VM. Only Client2 should be able to access it.
Check if you can access the client1 website from Firewall VM.
Check if you can access the client1 website from Client 2 vm.
Allow SSH to firewall VM only from Client2 VM.
Check ssh to firewall vm from client1. 
Check ssh to firewall vm from client2


Assuming your setup is:
Device
IP
Firewall
192.168.25.254
Client1
192.168.25.10
Client2
192.168.25.20


1. Block Ping to Firewall from Both Clients
On Firewall VM
Block ICMP Echo Request to firewall itself:
iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.25.0/24 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j DROP

Effect
Client1:
ping 192.168.25.254

Fails.
Client2:
ping 192.168.25.254

Fails.

2. Block Ping from Client1 to Client2
On Firewall VM
iptables -A FORWARD \
-s 192.168.25.10 \
-d 192.168.25.20 \
-p icmp \
--icmp-type echo-request \
-j DROP

Effect
Client1:
ping 192.168.25.20

Fails.
Client2:
ping 192.168.25.10

Still works unless separately blocked.

3. Save Rules
Rocky/CentOS:
iptables-save > /root/fw_rules.txt

Verify:
cat /root/fw_rules.txt


4. Flush FORWARD Chain
On Firewall VM
iptables -F FORWARD

Verify:
iptables -L FORWARD -n -v

Expected:
Chain FORWARD (policy ACCEPT)
target     prot opt source destination

No rules.

5. Install Apache on Client1
On Client1
sudo dnf install httpd -y

Start service:
sudo systemctl enable httpd
sudo systemctl start httpd

Check:
sudo systemctl status httpd


6. Create index.html
On Client1
echo "CLIENT1 WEB SERVER" | sudo tee /var/www/html/index.html

Verify:
curl localhost

Output:
CLIENT1 WEB SERVER


7. Block Firewall Access to Client1 Website
Website:
192.168.25.10:80

On Firewall VM
iptables -A OUTPUT \
-d 192.168.25.10 \
-p tcp \
--dport 80 \
-j REJECT

Effect
Firewall cannot open:
curl http://192.168.25.10

Fails.

8. Allow Client2 Access to Client1 Website
On Firewall VM
iptables -A FORWARD \
-s 192.168.25.20 \
-d 192.168.25.10 \
-p tcp \
--dport 80 \
-j ACCEPT

Effect
Client2:
curl http://192.168.25.10

Works.

9. Test from Firewall
On Firewall VM
curl http://192.168.25.10

Expected:
Connection refused

or timeout.
Because OUTPUT rule blocks it.

10. Test from Client2
On Client2
curl http://192.168.25.10

Expected:
CLIENT1 WEB SERVER


11. Allow SSH to Firewall Only from Client2
On Firewall VM
Allow Client2:
iptables -A INPUT \
-s 192.168.25.20 \
-p tcp \
--dport 22 \
-j ACCEPT

Block everyone else:
iptables -A INPUT \
-p tcp \
--dport 22 \
-j DROP


12. Test from Client1
On Client1
ssh root@192.168.25.254

Expected:
Connection timed out

or
Connection refused

depending on policy.

13. Test from Client2
On Client2
ssh root@192.168.25.254

Expected:
Password:

SSH login should work.

Verification Commands
Firewall
iptables -L INPUT -n -v

Shows:
ICMP DROP
SSH ACCEPT (Client2)
SSH DROP (Others)

iptables -L OUTPUT -n -v

Shows:
HTTP block to Client1

iptables -L FORWARD -n -v

Shows:
Client1 → Client2 ICMP DROP
Client2 → Client1 HTTP ACCEPT
These are the exact commands typically expected in DITISS/NDC iptables practicals.

